  1. Using the flights dataset, create a function that filters the data frame to only include records from a single originating airport (column name origin). In other words, it should let you enter an origin airport and return all the records from just that airport.
filter_airport <- function(airport){
  result <- filter(flights, origin == airport)
  return(result)
}

  1. Similarly, using the flights dataset, create a function that:

  • filters the data frame to only include records from a single originating airport (column name origin), and then

  • aggregates (i.e.Â counts) the results by airline (carrier) to show how many flights each airline has from that airport.

filter_airport <- function(airport){
  flight_data_set <- filter(flights, origin == airport)
  result <- flight_data_set %>% 
    group_by(carrier) %>% 
    summarise(count=n())
  return(result)
}

#example
filter_airport("LGA")

Credentials

First step to using tidycensus to interact with the U.S. Census Bureauâs API is loading your API Key credential. You thankfully only have to do this one time on your computer and it will create a little file that remembers it each time afterwards.

If you havenât already done so, make sure to request your personal API key from the Census here:

https://api.census.gov/data/key_signup.html

Uncomment the code below and run it to install your API key on your computer. Again, you only have to do this one time, so once itâs install you can comment out the code again so it doesnât run every single time.

Now, using the mutate() function, create a new column that contains the percentage of people with a bachelorâs or higher degree for each state. Remember that because the Census counts people with a bachelorâs only vs.Â a graduate degree separately, youâll need to combine those categories before making your calculation against the total population column.

new_clean_allstates_wide <- clean_allstates_wide %>% 
  mutate(bach_or_higher = education_bachelorsE + education_gradprofessE)

pctdata_new_clean_allstates_wide <- new_clean_allstates_wide %>% 
  mutate(pct_ed_bach_or_higher = (bach_or_higher / education_totalE) *100)
